# CEO Review (Plan) — bowling-shirt-designer

Reviewed planner.out + plan-eval.out against brief and richness-10 target.

## Verdict rationale
- **Honors Michael's explicit ask.** Planner correctly overrode intake's downgrade: Next.js 14 (static export, basePath-matched) + a REAL PHP microservice proxied through Flask. This is the single most important thing to get right for this client and it is right.
- **Demo IS the pitch.** Architecture maps 1:1 to the posting's two pain points: Zustand guarded store answers `undefined is not an object` / dead-clicks; dynamically-imported code-split canvas answers homepage bounce/script-blocking. That alignment turns the build into live proof, not narrative. Strong strategic call.
- **Richness 10, bounded.** 1 hero (upload pattern + live 3D + text-on-back decal) + 2 supporting, procedural mesh (no GLTF risk), canvas-generated patterns (no CDN/license risk), PHP gated on runtime `php --version` with clean Flask-only fallback. Ambitious but every risk has a mitigation.
- **Design is bespoke + industry-fit.** Retro-bowling/60s Americana + clean SaaS, palette validated against real brands, zero michaelwegter.com tokens.

## Notes carried forward (non-blocking, for demo-builder)
1. Java/MySQL/Spring Boot/MongoDB "mandatory" tags are Upwork tag-spam, irrelevant to the actual JS-audit project — cover letter gets ONE transferable-backend sentence, no over-promising.
2. Decal on back face must be Y=PI; validate visually.
3. ~12-file budget is tight for Next.js — stack functionality per file.
4. First-paint = zero console errors is a hard gate; canvas must stay out of the critical path (ssr:false confirmed).

Plan is genuinely good enough to build a winning demo at richness 10. No re-entry, no redirect needed.

VERDICT: pass
